Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in unsupervised syntactic induction lies in learning meaningful hierarchical structure without access to explicit annotations. Recent work has explored leveraging attention patterns (Paper 1), differentiable tree-based architectures (Paper 2), and clustering of contextual representations (Paper 3) to extract syntax implicitly. However, these methods remain largely confined to the linguistic modality, often ignoring the rich grounding cues available in vision. Human language acquisition is inherently multimodal—children learn syntax not just from sequences of words but through alignment with visual scenes where objects, actions, and their relationships are concretely instantiated. This motivates a framework that jointly optimizes for syntactic coherence and cross-modal alignment in an end-to-end manner, without supervision.

My idea builds on this intuition by proposing a model that induces syntax *through* visual-semantic alignment, using vision as a supervisory signal proxy. Unlike prior work that treats syntax and vision separately or uses vision only for downstream tasks, I propose a unified architecture where syntactic structure emerges as a latent variable optimized to maximize both (a) consistency in hierarchical composition over text and (b) alignment between compositional meaning and visual scenes. Crucially, the syntactic tree is modeled as a differentiable latent variable via a soft CKY parser, enabling gradient-based optimization, while the visual-semantic alignment acts as an unsupervised objective that guides structural induction. This differs from Papers 1–3 by introducing a *cross-modal pressure* that shapes syntactic hypotheses—words that co-refer to coherent visual regions should be grouped together syntactically. Moreover, it avoids reliance on pre-defined syntactic categories or substitutability heuristics, instead letting structure emerge from multimodal coherence.

